name: Graham Stephan

full_text: RT @GrahamStephan: Here's a simple way to avoid Government shutdowns: \n\nYou just pass a law that says every time there is a Govt. shutdown,…
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
If you are curious as to why the Congress can't work out an agreement to avoid the shutdown: 

Normally, if politicians operated efficiently, a budget would pass through the House of Representatives, get approved by the Senate, and then be signed off by the president to go into effect.

But in 2023, there's a big issue: The House of Representatives is led by Republicans but the Senate is majority Democrat. For a bill to pass, everyone is going to have to come to an agreement, which means, one side is going to have to compromise more than they want.

Further complicating the matter is that an agreement cannot be reached even among the Republican members.

Even though I generally stay out of politics, for those who are curious exactly what this disagreement is about, it appears as though Kevin McCarthy, the House majority leader, has made promises to the right, ultra-right, and moderates in order to keep his job and stay in power.

As you might imagine, it's impossible to satisfy all of those demands and appease everyone, without splitting his group in half. 

So, his choice is simple: 

Try to push through spending cuts that would be dead on arrival in the Senate, thereby causing a Government Shutdown, or, give in to the majority demand to keep the money flowing and risk his job.

Something’s going to have to give.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
"Marry the house, date the rate"

With mortgage rates at 7% and the median mortgage payment at $2,162 per month, this is the advice that many real estate agents are giving.

The idea is simple: When rates are high, competition is low, and it's easier for you to get a house you like. Since a house is a long-term commitment, you might as well "marry" it. As for the high mortgage payments, they depend on the Fed rate, and if rates drop down the line, you can refinance and save on payments.

But that's a BIG if.

Refinances can make sense if:
- Your term increases, but you pay less monthly or
- You pay more monthly, but your loan is paid off earlier

One risk with this strategy is: Buying into a house you can't afford, thinking that you can refinance at any time down the line. But if interest rates stay the same or go higher, you could be stuck paying huge monthly payments for a long time. Housing is everyone's biggest expense and it might burn a hole in your pocket.

The other risk is panic-buying into an overvalued property in a hot market. If it's a house you're going to stay in for a while, it's one thing. But cash-out refinancing is going to be a problem if the value of your home drops.

Finally, refinancing isn't free – it can cost 2 to 6% of your loan amount. Even if the rate drops, a high cost of refinancing would mean that the deal isn't worth it. And if you refinance and the rate drops further, you're going to facepalm that you didn't time the bottom.

NOBODY can predict interest rates, and while you could take advantage of a refinance in case rates do drop, planning your financial strategy for the next 15 to 30 years gambling on the interest rate can be a bad move.

If you're marrying the house and dating the rate, make sure it's a house you really like, and you can afford the payments even if the rates don't go your way.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
"Every action you take is a vote for the type of person you wish to become."

James Clear's book "Atomic Habits" is a practical guide to make and break habits – and it got me thinking about how much of personal finance is driven by habits. 

Most beginners tend to look for the one secret that's going to make them rich, but building wealth is about consistent action that compounds to create something bigger. 

When I take pot-shots at Starbucks coffees or Avocado toast, it's not about the one-time spend. I'm a Sushi lover myself and I know the joys of good food. But diluting your money across a hundred tiny spends gives you so much less satisfaction compared to saving up for what you really enjoy and investing the rest towards financial freedom. 

Don't beat yourself up about an extravagant treat – but watch which financial actions you repeat consistently, because that's where you're bleeding money.

Financial well-being isn't a one-time achievement. 
It's how you spend your days and how you spend in your days.

full_text:
An Airbnb host in LA let a guest stay on for a few extra days in 2022. 

A year and a half later, she still hadn't vacated – She paid no rent and demanded $100,000 to move out. 

Here's the story of "the tenant from hell":

Let's call the landlord Bob and the tenant Jane.
"Bob" has been renting out his guesthouse on Airbnb since 2019. It's in a premium area in LA.
In late 2021, "Jane" approached him. She wanted a six-month stay at the guesthouse. 
They worked out a rate of $105 per night – around $21k for 187 nights.

Jane seemed polite enough till her lease expired in March 2022.
She asked for more time, and Bob refused. But then he let her stay on till April 12 – without a lease agreement. 
This was a terrible mistake.
At this point, Airbnb was out of the picture. 
Jane stopped paying rent.

Since then, Bob tried many things to get Jane to leave.
He tried moving her to a hotel to get the house repaired. 
He offered $2,000 for moving assistance. Finally, he sued her after the deadline.

The case lasted for more than a year, and things didn't go in Bob's favor. Jane's lawyer dragged out the case saying:
- The ADU didn't have a certificate of occupancy (BIG mistake).
- The ADU had an unpermitted shower (Really?)
- Jane had chemical sensitivities and COVID risk, and could not be evicted.
- Bob's kids play loud music to harass Jane (in his own house!)
- That Bob had no license or lease agreement – and he couldn't charge rent on the unit.

That last point seems very fishy.
It looks like the tenant had known all along that there were technical problems with the property, and she steered things toward a legal battle knowing the landlord wouldn't win.
The court favored her, and she wasn't required to move out.
Jane demanded $100,000 from Bob to move out, as a "relocation fee."

Imagine living on the same property, a few feet away, from someone you're fighting a legal battle with!
Paparazzi followed Jane around every time she left the house.
Bob didn't feel safe living in his own house. 
The situation was terrible for both of them.
Finally, she vacated after 570 days – and Bob has lost $58,000 in rent.

My sympathies are with Bob here: 
I've had two bad experiences of tenants squatting for weeks and months after their lease lapsed. I couldn't get them to evict.
One of them even trashed the place before finally leaving, causing thousands of dollars in damage. 
Bob could have avoided all this by being more careful with the legal stuff – but it looks like he was targeted and taken advantage of here.

The law favors tenants heavily. Once you lock in a tenant, it's very hard to evict them.
Some tenants take advantage of this. They know all the loopholes and technicalities of the system. They're called "Professional Tenants."
Renting out to a professional tenant can lose you thousands of dollars in rent and damages.
Worse, it can turn your life into a stressful nightmare.

I'm going to drop a step-by-step guide on how to steer clear of professional tenants. 
Follow me @grahamstephan to make sure you don't miss it.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
Today, the world’s gold stock is about 170,000 metric tons. If all of this gold were melded together, it would form a cube of about 68 feet per side. (Picture it fitting comfortably within a baseball infield.) At $1,750 per ounce, its value would be $9.6 trillion. Call this cube pile A.

Let’s now create a pile B costing an equal amount. For that, we could buy all U.S. cropland, plus 16 Exxon Mobils, and still have $1 trillion left over. Can you imagine an investor with $9.6 trillion selecting pile A over pile B?

A century from now, the 400 million acres of farmland will have produced staggering amounts of corn, wheat, cotton, and other crops. Exxon Mobil will probably have delivered trillions of dollars in dividends and also hold assets worth trillions (and, remember, you get 16 Exxon’s).

The 170,000 tons of gold will be unchanged in size and still incapable of producing anything. You can fondle the cube, but it will not respond.

-- Warren Buffett
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
I am tired of this narrative. 

There's very little data to support that Wall Street is buying up houses. 

If anything, this is a ploy to take the focus away from the actual problems of high-interest rates, low inventory, and limited development 🧵.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
Here are the simple facts:

Mortgage rates are the highest they have been since 2000.

Housing inventory is at the lowest it’s been since 1999. 

60% of homeowners have a rate locked in below 4%.

In the last 20 years, incomes have risen 80% – but home prices have risen 250%
name: Graham Stephan

full_text: The reality is that only 1.6% of all single-family rental homes in America are owned by Private Equity. \n\nThe remaining 98.4% are owned by everyday people like you and me.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text: The focus should be on the fact that low interest rates completely turned the economy upside down. \n\nWe're now facing the consequences of artificially stimulating the economy.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text: And almost all of these large investors were funded by everyday people who invested their spare cash into pensions, retirement plans, and real estate investment trusts. \n\nThe returns flowed back to the investors.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text: The way I see it, based on all the numbers from verified sources, the real reason housing prices are unaffordable is due to the aftershock of decades of artificially low rates, restrictive zoning that makes it difficult to add inventory, and a surplus of demand from home buyers.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
That's it. 

It's not sexy, it's not dramatic, and it doesn't give us a faceless corporation to blame for its greed causing our problems. 

But that's the truth.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text: A good idea can change the way you think.\n\nHere are 10 of them, from my favorite money and investing books:
name: Graham Stephan

full_text: 1. The psychology of money\n\nYour wealth depends less on your intelligence than your habits and your life experiences. https://t.co/pYrrzTATPK
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
2. The intelligent investor

The market is a voting machine in the short term and a weighing machine in the long term.

Working on how you respond to surprises is way more profitable than picking a winning stock. https://t.co/INVh8Ne08G
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
3. Your Money or Your Life

You trade life energy to make money, to spend it on things you like. 

Optimize for life energy rather than money, to enjoy what you value the most. https://t.co/yOd16kfrSQ
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
4. The Richest Man in Babylon

Pay yourself first – Save at least 10% of what you earn before paying expenses. 

It's a subtle shift but it changes your priority from immediate consumption to wealth-building. https://t.co/RYNB2I8sfW
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
5. The 4-Hour Workweek

Don't postpone the life you want to live till retirement, by forcing yourself to stay in a miserable situation.

Instead, try to design your life in a way that balances your obligations with the things you really want to do, in small ways – starting now. https://t.co/by3f1bu3eF
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
6. The paradox of choice

Don't look for "the best choice" always.

Instead, settle for "good enough" in most areas and focus on "the best" only in the few areas that really matter to you. 

This will save you time, money, and energy. https://t.co/oVHE7BUC9i
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
7. The Millionaire Fastlane

Detach your income from your time. 

If your income depends on the hours you work, there's an upper limit to your wealth.

But an idea or a product or an asset that makes money while you sleep is the way to build unbounded upside. https://t.co/WVpCKk3wZw
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
8. The Millionaire Next Door

Most self-made millionaires didn't get there with an extraordinarily high income.

Instead, they built their wealth by living below their means and investing the difference. https://t.co/W1fNAooXg6
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
9. The Total Money Makeover

If you're trying to get out of a bad financial situation, the two things that will have immediate impact are:

- Working on your debt
- Sticking to a budget

Discipline beats luck while building wealth. https://t.co/NjZPs1qScD
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
10. Thinking, fast and slow

A lot of our decision-making is unconscious and reflexive.

Understand your own biases. 

You won't be tricked as easily into spending on things you don't need, or investing in things you don't understand. https://t.co/wkyQs79x0F
name: Graham Stephan

Warren Buffett is an investing legend.

But he built his wealth before his investing success.

Here's why investing won't make you rich: https://t.co/nKBXtguhD6
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
Sam Parr said this on David Perell's podcast: 

"You should look at the habits of successful people before they got big. 

A 13 year old basketball player should look at 𝘄𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗟𝗲𝗯𝗿𝗼𝗻 𝗝𝗮𝗺𝗲𝘀 𝘄𝗮𝘀 𝗱𝗼𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗮𝘁 𝟭𝟯, not what he’s doing today."

I agree.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
A lot of beginners try to learn from Warren Buffett. 

There's definitely value in understanding his principles for any investor. 

But you need to understand 𝙝𝙤𝙬 𝙝𝙚 𝙜𝙤𝙩 𝙝𝙞𝙨 𝙨𝙩𝙖𝙧𝙩.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
Buffett started his partnership in 1956, after quitting his job as a securities analyst. 

He retired at 25, as a father. 

In some ways, Buffett was the pioneer of the FIRE movement. 

In his words: https://t.co/tveSMFsGch
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
But how did he build his nest egg? 

Simple. He worked for it.

• He sold newspapers as a student.
• He started multiple businesses, including renting out pinball machines.
• He was a securities salesman for 4 years.
• He worked as a securities analyst at Graham Newman.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
All of his initial capital before he started managing money was either business income or savings from his salary. 

Buffett is famous for having a 20-30% annual return for decades. 

But from 1950 to 1955, his capital went from $9,800 to $127,000 – an annual increase 𝗼𝗳 𝟲𝟳%.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
Important lesson: 

For most young people, the fastest way to increase your net worth is 𝗯𝘆 𝗶𝗻𝘃𝗲𝘀𝘁𝗶𝗻𝗴 𝗶𝗻 𝘆𝗼𝘂𝗿𝘀𝗲𝗹𝗳. 

The rate at which your salary or business income grows can be rapid before it hits an upper limit.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
Buffett kept learning and growing his investment knowledge till he was ready to "retire".

There's no reason you can't do the same :)

full_text:
Rents in the US are getting higher.

A book about flies cost $24 Million on Amazon.

These two things have something in common 🧵: https://t.co/DF0Vmz0K4E
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
In 2011, a postdoc researcher logged on to Amazon to buy a copy of "The making of a fly." 

The book was somewhat rare – but the online price was absurd.

15 used copies at $35.54.
And 2 new copies at $1.73 Million and $2.1 Million!
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
The researcher logged in the next day. 

The number had gone up to $2.8 million.

Turns out – the two sellers were setting the price using an automated algorithm.

Both algorithms were looking at the other and automatically raising prices.

There was no upper limit.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
The prices finally hit an absurd $24 Million on Amazon!

The sellers manually reset the price.

That's what happens when algorithms lose touch with reality.

And now, it might be affecting rental prices.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
The Washington Attorney General's office recently filed a case on 14 landlords and the software company RealPage.

The charge? Price-fixing.

They allege that this "cartel" is making housing unaffordable for tenants.

How? https://t.co/jzZKkaUR8f
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
RealPage's software is used by landlords and portfolio managers.

It uses 20+ years data to help them decide:

1. What rent they should charge
2. When they should leave a flat vacant

The analyst who invented the software says there's no way it can underperform a manual analyst.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
Meanwhile, the DOJ is also investigating RealPage.

This case is huge. 

Everything from E-commerce to Hotels to Travel runs on algorithms for setting prices and optimizing business.

If there's a precedent here, the way algorithms are regulated may totally change.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
Smart people have higher incomes. 
Patient people have higher wealth.

In the 1970s, a team at the Ohio State University studied over 7,000 people to answer: Do you have to be smart to be rich?

Turns out, every IQ point raises your income by $234 to $616.

But it says nothing about your wealth.

In fact, higher IQ actually increases the chances of being in financial difficulty, like:
- Problems with paying bills
- Going bankrupt
- Reaching credit card limits

Wealth isn't about smarts alone. 
It's about financial habits – how much you save, how much you invest, and how well you understand your own pitfalls.

full_text:
Athletes are some of the highest-paid people in America.
Yet, a surprising number of them go bankrupt.
Here's what I found and what you can do differently:

In 2009, Sports Illustrated estimated that about 60% of NBA players are broke within 5 years of retirement. 78% of NFL players file for bankruptcy just 2 years after they retire. Is this because they don't know how to handle the money and fame they haven't received all their lives? Or is it because athletes have extremely short careers compared to the average person who could work till they retire at 60? There's a bit of both, but there's a bigger reason.

It's what Morgan Housel calls "Social Debt": Sometimes when you're massively successful, it doesn't feel like that success is yours – it belongs to everyone who is connected to you, even remotely. Shaq earned $20M on his first paycheck. He bought a car worth $250k. 

But then his dad asked for a similar car. 
His mom asked for one too. 
He thought that buying a $7M house was a good idea. He bought expensive gifts for his friends.
By the time he got the call from his accountant that $20M was less than $10M after taxes in CA, he had blown more than $8M.

This could also be why so many lottery winners tend to blow their winnings.

What's the solution? Forget your friends when you win big?
Not at all. 
Your life is rich because of the relationships you maintain, and beyond a point, more money isn't going to fulfill the search for meaning.
But don't cave to social pressure either.

Someone who upgrades their lifestyle and tries to lift everyone along with them just cannot sustain it.
A millionaire living like a multi-millionaire and someone making minimum wage trying to live like a millionaire are going to end up the same way – broke.

Instead, live a frugal lifestyle, allow yourself to enjoy good things, and focus on building financial stability.
Help others grow while being clear about your boundaries.
You can't help others if you aren't in a good place yourself.

Maybe this is why Shaq tells his kids "We ain't rich. I'm rich". 🤣

This isn't just good advice for athletes or lottery winners though – Anyone looking to build wealth and trying to hold off on peer pressure can benefit from this approach.

How do you think you would handle a sudden lifestyle upgrade?
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
Nobody wants to sell their house because 99% have a mortgage less than the current rate. Here's a crazy solution:

Let people take their mortgage with them to the next house.

Let me explain: https://t.co/0v1Sh4jl9r
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
In the UK and Canada, there's this concept called a "portable mortgage".

When people move from one house to another, they can take their loan with them.

They just need to pay the remaining balance of the loan but they can keep the same interest rate.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
This works in the UK and Canada for two reasons:

1. Loans are paid out over 25 to 30 years, but rates aren't locked in. Rates are renewed every 5 to 6 years.

2. So lenders compete to give the best rates. Portable mortgages are a good alternative to variable-rate mortgages.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text: In the US, loans are fixed for 30 years\n\nRefinancing is usually a more attractive option for homebuyers, because they could get a cheaper rate.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text: Portable mortgages don't fit in neatly with the mortgage securities market in the US. \n\nThey have to be custom-made for specific buyers, and there's no tax credit like refinancing.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text:
But here's why lenders in the US could benefit from offering portable loans:

1. It's a unique niche in a rising interest rate environment.

2. Many millennials and GenZ-ers want mobility, so a lender who facilitates portable loans would capture that market.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text: 3. They could charge a transfer fee that is cheaper than getting a new loan at a higher rate. \n\nThis makes it a better option for people looking to sell and buy.
name: Graham Stephan

full_text: This would free up so much inventory and let people downsize – because they could profit off their current homes without losing their  mortgages.\n\nIf any lender takes the lead on this when interest rates are high, they could capture a lot of loyal customers for a long time.
name: Graham Stephan
